BODY = """
<h2>Why Dubai Became the City of Gold</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Geography.</strong> Dubai sits between African and Asian producing regions and the subcontinent's enormous gold demand &mdash; a few flight hours from both supply and consumption.</li>
<li><strong>Infrastructure.</strong> Accredited refineries, extensive vaulting, specialist <a href="/knowledge/how-gold-is-transported-securely/">valuables logistics</a>, and an airport built for transit trade.</li>
<li><strong>Institutions.</strong> The DMCC free zone hosts the precious metals trading community with its own regulatory framework, accreditation standards and exchange infrastructure; the emirate's customs procedures for declared gold are established and efficient.</li>
<li><strong>Market depth.</strong> A dense community of refiners, bullion dealers, jewellery manufacturers and buyers means arriving metal meets immediate liquidity &mdash; and competitive terms.</li>
<li><strong>Tax treatment.</strong> Favourable treatment of investment-grade bullion supports the trading economics (specific tax rules change; current advice applies).</li>
</ul>

<h2>The Dubai Gold Ecosystem</h2>
<p><strong>DMCC</strong> &mdash; the free zone authority at the centre of the trade: licensing member firms, operating accreditation including the Dubai Good Delivery standard, and aligning local practice with <a href="/knowledge/oecd-gold-supply-chain-guidance/">OECD responsible sourcing rules</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Refineries</strong> &mdash; Dubai's accredited refineries receive dor&eacute; flows, primarily from Africa, refining to kilobars and other regional products &mdash; the operation described in <a href="/knowledge/how-gold-refineries-operate/">How Gold Refineries Operate</a>.</p>
<p><strong>The physical souk and wholesale market</strong> &mdash; from the traditional Gold Souk's retail trade to wholesale kilobar dealing, Dubai quotes physical premiums and discounts to the international price that reflect regional demand in real time.</p>
<p><strong>Banks and trade finance</strong> &mdash; regional and international banks provide the <a href="/knowledge/what-is-an-mt700-dlc/">letters of credit</a> and financing that move metal through the hub.</p>

<h2>How a CIF Dubai Transaction Uses the Hub</h2>
<p>The structure described in <a href="/knowledge/what-is-a-cif-gold-transaction/">What Is a CIF Gold Transaction?</a> relies on Dubai's institutional features at each step: declared import through established customs channels; delivery to an accredited refinery whose <a href="/knowledge/how-does-a-gold-refinery-assay-work/">assay</a> both parties can credit; settlement at benchmark-referenced prices into a deep local market; and onward sale of refined output into immediate regional demand. The hub's credibility is precisely what makes &ldquo;CIF Dubai&rdquo; a recognised, bankable delivery basis rather than just a destination.</p>

<h2>Compliance Realities</h2>
<p>Dubai's scale has historically attracted scrutiny over high-risk gold flows, and the response has been a tightening framework: DMCC rules aligned to OECD guidance, UAE federal AML regulation of the precious metals sector, and the same <a href="/knowledge/sanctions-compliance-for-precious-metals/">sanctions screening</a> obligations that apply across the international market. The practical consequence for sellers: Dubai's reputable refineries and dealers run full due diligence &mdash; provable origin, licensed export and clean custody are entry requirements here as everywhere in the legitimate market.</p>

<h2>Example</h2>
<p>A West African exporter ships 30 kg of dor&eacute; CIF Dubai monthly. The metal clears Dubai customs as declared valuables cargo, is assayed and refined at an accredited refinery, and is settled at the LBMA-referenced contract price. The refined kilobars sell into wholesale demand the same week, often at a premium reflecting regional conditions. For the exporter, Dubai delivers three things at once: a credible settlement venue, competitive refining terms, and a buyer's market for the output &mdash; the full hub function in a single transaction cycle.</p>
"""

